def isBipartite(graph: List[List[int]]) -> bool:
    def dfs(node: int, color: int) -> bool:
        if colors[node]:
            return colors[node] == color

        colors[node] = color
        for neighbor in graph[node]:
            if not dfs(neighbor, 3 - color):
                return False

        return True

    n = len(graph)
    colors = [0] * n

    for i in range(n):
        if not colors[i] and not dfs(i, 1):
            return False

    return True
```

    The algorithm is based on a Depth First Search (DFS). We iterate over all nodes, performing a DFS on the nodes that have not been assigned a color yet.

In the DFS, we first check if the node has a color assigned. If it has, we return true if the assigned color matches the expected color. If the node does not have a color assigned, we assign the expected color to it, and perform the DFS on all its neighbors with the alternate color (3 - color). If any of these DFS return false, we return false. Otherwise, we return true.

After iterating all nodes, if none of them returned false, then the graph is bipartite.

This algorithm does not depend on the specific programming language, but the syntax for the DFS and color assignments will vary according to the language used.

